    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i keep seeing people call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why do they use that word specifically? is there something actually weird or unexplained about how the connection works?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The phrase \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Einstein to express his deep skepticism about quantum entanglement, specifically because it seemed to violate the classical principle that information cannot travel faster than light. While the connection itself doesn't technically allow for faster-than-light communication (since the outcome is random and cannot be controlled), the instantaneous collapse of the wavefunction across vast distances felt to Einstein like a \"spooky\" violation of locality. Modern physics accepts that while the correlation is instantaneous, no usable information is transmitted, so the \"action\" is real but doesn't break relativity in the way Einstein feared.",
      "source": "target",
