    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "idk, it still feels kinda creepy that it's instant like that. like, if a particle is on the other side of the galaxy, how does it \"know\" what the first one did exactly at that moment? it almost feels like there's some hidden mechanism or something interfering behind the scenes.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That intuition is actually shared by many physicists, even today, because our brains are wired to understand the world through \"local realism\"—the idea that objects have definite properties and influence only their immediate surroundings. The \"creepiness\" comes from the fact that in entanglement, the particles don't just \"know\" each other's states; their states are genuinely undefined until measurement, and the act of measuring one immediately defines the other across any distance. However, there is no hidden mechanism or signal traveling between them; the universe simply operates under non-local quantum rules where distance doesn't limit how the shared wavefunction behaves. While it feels like magic to our classical intuition, it has been rigorously tested and confirmed, proving that the universe is fundamentally more interconnected than we ever imagined.",
      "source": "target",
